1 The play assigns no cause for Amphitruo’s residence at Thebes, nor does this concern the plot in any way. Apollo- dorus (Bibl. 2. 48) narrates that Amphitryon had accidentally slain Electryon, the father of his betrothed wife Alcmena, and had fied ‘to Thebes, where Creon was reigning. Hence, he tells us, Amphitryon led an expedition against the Teleboae, to take vengeance on their king, Pterelaus, who had killed Alcmena’s brother. This differs from the play which repre- sents Amphitruo merely as Creon's general against the Tele- boae, and the quarrel with them, apparently, as Creon’s quarrel. The play differs from Apollodorus in other respects also. The latter represents the night 35 three times its ordin· ary length: Plautus simply as somewhat longer. According to Apollodorus, Hercules was eight months old when he strangled the serpents z Plautus represents him as just born.
